Title. 
Replication of a research claim from Bischetti et al, 2020
RR Team. 
Erin M. Buchanan, PhD, Alexa R. Schlyfestone, Raquel Huggins
Harrisburg University of Science and Technology
Claim Summary.
This replication tests the claim that COVID-19 humor will be more aversive than humor on more benign topics, specifically that COVID-verbal pictures will be rated more aversive than non-COVID-verbal pictures. This claim was tested with a linear mixed model with crossed effects for participants, items, and state. Note that the claim or paper does not include age, but their provided script does. 
Replication Criteria.
Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is a statistically significant effect (alpha = .05, two tailed) in the same pattern as the original study on the focal hypothesis test (H*). For this study, a successful replication is a significant difference in Aversiveness, such that COVID-19 humor is more aversive than non-COVID-19 humor.

Replication Result.
The results from our updated model (see below) do not support a replication of the Bischetti et al. The mixed model showed no difference in aversiveness ratings between COVID-verbal and non-COVID-verbal items, b = -0.08, SE = 0.05, t(219.30) = -1.71, p = 8.785487e-02 (.088). The marginal means suggest the COVID-verbal (M = 0.65, SE = 0.04) items were only slightly higher than the non-COVID-verbal (M = 0.57, SE = 0.04). The fixed effects are included below. Note that the comparison group for these estimates is the COVID-verbal condition. 

Deviations from preregistration.
No deviations were made for the study delivery; however, we did make a few deviations for the payment during the study. As noted in our analysis script, the server we were running the study on crashed while many participants were taking the study. We paused the study immediately. We then went through the data to see what we had and notified participants they could finish the study if they desired (once the server was back up). We paid participants who completed at least half the study with half the incentive ($3.00) to account for the server crash. We then opened the rest of the slots back up to new participants on Prolific based on the money we had left to complete the study. Therefore, we recruited more than 1000 participants, but several only completed half the study. We used all data points in our analyses, as mixed models can account for this type of missing data. 
Our analyses scripts were also updated:
Reproducibility information about packages was added to the top of the script. 
We deidentified the data, as Prolific IDs may not be anonymous. 
We excluded data points from testers, as these rows are part of the raw data download from formr. 
We removed duplicates from the server crash.
We added a state that a participant emailed us to add.
We rescaled age from year of birth to age by subtracting 2021 – age. 
When writing the original code, we did not put the labels in the right order to get the COVID-verbal versus non-COVID-verbal. These levels were reordered. 
A notable change from preregistration involves the model formula. We originally tried using the same model formula as the online provided script, albeit this model formula is not well described in the paper (i.e., it does not mention age). This model would not converge properly. We tried several different optimizers, which also would not converge. Therefore, we created a model with only one parameter and slowly added parameters until the model stopped working. It was determined that the age random slopes were the problematic parameter, and it was removed. Otherwise, the random slopes and intercepts were included. Further, the paper reports what we think are marginal means from the model, but this code was not included in the original script (ours or theirs). We added emmeans to calculate these values. 
Description of materials provided.
Methods and Materials: https://osf.io/pcu9g/ 
The Bischetti_Survey excel file includes the formr coding to create the survey. This format includes all the items and answer choices, which allows recreation of the survey by uploading into formr. 
Note: This survey was broken into two parts, which was a practical problem for implementation in formr. From our experience, the surveys can bog down if you have more than 400 rows of items/submit buttons/instructions. Therefore, we split it in half to have the survey run better. In formr, you would just import both surveys, then set up a run to show survey 1 first, then survey 2 second. 
The Materials document file represents the items shown to participants as a word document that was submitted to the IRB. 
The Images folder contains all the pictures shown to participants, labeled as they were implemented in formr. On the server, we put all these into one folder, however for easier understanding online, we included subfolders of each image type. 
Data: https://osf.io/shd6r/ 
Bischetti_DataDictionary excel file includes a data dictionary for the dataset with all variables explained and choice numbers identified. Note, there are two tabs, one for each part of the survey.
To match the pictures to their item label, the Bischetti_Survey in the methods file can be used. The analysis code also demonstrates how to merge this information. 
Bischetti_Survey_deidentify csv file includes the deidentified data for each half of the survey. This data was simply processed to exclude Prolific ID numbers, which are not anonymous. You can see the code that created the new column and dropped the Prolific ID column in our Analysis folder. 
Bischetti_Survey_example csv file is an example dataset that was used to provide preregistration code. 
Analysis: https://osf.io/u7evb/ 
The Analysis rmd (R markdown) and html file are the original preregistered scripts that provided an outline for the analysis.
The Analysis_updated rmd and html file are the updated analysis scripts with the fixed analysis and new code described above. This file can be used to recreate our analyses. Note, you will need to download the full OSF structure to recreate these analyses, as we incorporated the file structure into our script (i.e., it is expected that the markdown file is in a folder Analysis and the data is in a folder Data). Note that the versions of R and packages are provided at the top of the html report for full reproducibility. 
All materials will be made public.
Citation.
Bischetti, L., Canal, P., & Bambini, V. (2020). Funny but aversive: A large-scale survey on the emotional response to Covid-19 humor in the Italian population during the lockdown. https://doi.org/10.31234/osf.io/efk93 

